@page "/build/hardware"

<PageTitle>Hardware Guide</PageTitle>

<div class="wizard-page">
    <h2>Build Your Lab — Complete Hardware Guide</h2>
    <p class="wiz-explain">Everything you need to buy, where to buy it, how to wire it, and why each piece exists. Total cost: ~$250 for all electronics + sensors. No prior experience needed.</p>

    <div class="wiz-learn">
        <h3>What are we building?</h3>
        <p>A miniature laboratory controlled by 4 tiny computer chips (ESP32-S3, $4 each) connected to your WiFi. These chips control 17 instruments that together can synthesize mRNA medicine — the same technology used in COVID vaccines.</p>
        <p>Think of it like a kitchen: the ESP32 chips are the "smart plugs" that let you control every appliance from your phone (or in this case, from the Blazor WASM app in your browser).</p>

        <h3>The 4 ESP32 chips and what they control</h3>

        <div class="wiz-construct">
            <strong>ESP32 #1 — Controller ($4)</strong>
            <p>The main brain. Controls the core mRNA-making equipment:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Heat Block</strong> — a small aluminum block that keeps reactions at 37°C (body temperature), which is where the enzymes work best. Like a sous vide for biology.</li>
                <li><strong>UV Spectrophotometer</strong> — shines ultraviolet light through your sample to measure how much RNA you made and if it's pure. RNA absorbs UV at 260nm wavelength.</li>
                <li><strong>Centrifuge</strong> — spins tubes at 8,000 RPM to separate heavy molecules from light ones. Like a salad spinner but 1,000x faster.</li>
                <li><strong>Gel Electrophoresis</strong> — uses electricity (100 volts) to push RNA through a jelly-like gel. Smaller molecules move faster, so you can check if your RNA is the right size.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="wiz-construct">
            <strong>ESP32 #2 — Stepper Slave ($4)</strong>
            <p>Dedicated to the two syringe pumps — the most precision-critical equipment:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Syringe Pump A</strong> — slowly pushes mRNA solution through a tiny tube</li>
                <li><strong>Syringe Pump B</strong> — slowly pushes lipid (fat) solution through another tube</li>
                <li>Both meet at a T-junction where they mix at an exact 3:1 ratio to form lipid nanoparticles (the protective bubbles that carry mRNA into your cells)</li>
            </ul>
            <p>This chip has NO WiFi running — it's 100% dedicated to motor timing so the mixing ratio is perfectly precise.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="wiz-construct">
            <strong>ESP32 #3 — Environment ($4)</strong>
            <p>Monitors your lab environment and controls safety equipment:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>pH Meter</strong> — measures acidity of your buffer. Must be pH 4.0 for LNP mixing (too high or low = nanoparticles won't form)</li>
                <li><strong>Magnetic Stirrer</strong> — a spinning magnet under a plate that stirs liquids in a beaker. Dissolves lipids in ethanol.</li>
                <li><strong>Vortex Mixer</strong> — vibrates tubes to mix small volumes quickly</li>
                <li><strong>UV-C Lamp</strong> — 254nm ultraviolet light that kills bacteria. Sterilizes your workspace before each session.</li>
                <li><strong>Fume Hood Fan</strong> — sucks away ethanol vapors during LNP mixing. Safety first.</li>
                <li><strong>Room/Freezer/Fridge Monitors</strong> — continuously checks temperatures. Alarms if your -80°C freezer warms up (your mRNA would degrade).</li>
                <li><strong>Emergency Stop</strong> — big red button that kills all equipment instantly</li>
                <li><strong>Gas/Smoke Sensor</strong> — detects ethanol vapor leaks</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="wiz-construct">
            <strong>ESP32 #4 — QC & Imaging ($4)</strong>
            <p>Quality control instruments:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Gel Imager</strong> — camera + blue LED light that photographs your gel to verify RNA bands</li>
                <li><strong>DLS Particle Sizer</strong> — shines a laser through your LNPs and measures scattered light to calculate nanoparticle size (target: 60-100nm)</li>
                <li><strong>Turbidity Sensor</strong> — quick check of LNP concentration by measuring how cloudy the solution is</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

