        <h3>How to Assemble — Step by Step</h3>
        <p>You don't need to build everything at once. Start with ESP32 #1 (the main controller) and add the others later.</p>

        <h3>Step 1: Power Supply</h3>
        <div class="wiz-instruction">
            <p><strong>What:</strong> The 12V power supply converts your wall outlet to 12V DC that all the equipment needs. The LM2596 buck converter steps it down further to 5V for the ESP32 chips.</p>
            <p><strong>How:</strong> Plug the 12V PSU into the wall. Connect its (+) and (-) screw terminals to your breadboard power rails (red = +12V, blue = GND). Connect the LM2596's input to 12V, then turn its tiny brass screw with a screwdriver while measuring the output with your multimeter until it reads exactly 5.0V. Now you have both 12V and 5V available.</p>
        </div>

        <h3>Step 2: Flash ESP32 Firmware</h3>
        <div class="wiz-instruction">
            <p><strong>What:</strong> Upload the control software to each ESP32 chip via USB cable.</p>
            <p><strong>How:</strong> Install PlatformIO (free, runs in VS Code). Open the <code>src/Esp32</code> folder. Edit <code>include/config.h</code> — change <code>WIFI_SSID</code> and <code>WIFI_PASS</code> to your WiFi name and password. Connect ESP32 #1 via USB. Run <code>pio run -e controller -t upload</code>. Repeat for each ESP32 with the matching firmware target.</p>
        </div>

        <h3>Step 3: Wire the Heat Block</h3>
        <div class="wiz-instruction">
            <p><strong>What:</strong> A relay (electronic switch) connects the 12V power to a heating element. A temperature sensor tells the ESP32 the current temperature. The ESP32 runs a PID algorithm to hold the temperature steady at 37°C.</p>
            <p><strong>How:</strong> Connect ESP32 GPIO 5 to relay module IN1. Connect relay COM to 12V+, relay NO to PTC heater wire 1, heater wire 2 to GND. Connect DS18B20 sensor: red=3.3V, black=GND, yellow=GPIO 4 + 4.7kΩ resistor to 3.3V.</p>
        </div>

        <h3>Step 4: Wire the Syringe Pumps</h3>
        <div class="wiz-instruction">
            <p><strong>What:</strong> Each pump uses a stepper motor (moves in precise small steps) to push a syringe plunger. The A4988 driver board converts simple HIGH/LOW pulses from the ESP32 into the correct electrical pattern for the motor coils.</p>
            <p><strong>How:</strong> Connect A4988: VMOT=12V (add 100µF capacitor!), VDD=5V, GND=GND. Connect STEP/DIR/ENABLE to ESP32 GPIOs. Find motor coil pairs (touch two wires together, if shaft feels sticky = that's a pair). Connect pairs to 1A/1B and 2A/2B. <strong>CRITICAL:</strong> Set current limit BEFORE connecting motor — measure potentiometer voltage with multimeter, adjust to 0.96V.</p>
        </div>

        <h3>Step 5: Wire the UV Spectrophotometer</h3>
        <div class="wiz-instruction">
            <p><strong>What:</strong> Two UV LEDs (260nm and 280nm) shine through a small glass cuvette containing your sample. A photodiode on the other side measures how much light passes through. RNA absorbs 260nm light, so more absorption = more RNA.</p>
            <p><strong>How:</strong> Connect each UV LED through a MOSFET (IRLZ44N): ESP32 GPIO → MOSFET gate (+ 10kΩ pulldown to GND), LED through 100Ω resistor to 5V, LED cathode to MOSFET drain, MOSFET source to GND. Connect photodiode to OPA380 amplifier, amplifier output to ESP32 ADC pin.</p>
        </div>

        <h3>Order of Purchase</h3>
        <div class="wiz-instruction">
            <p><strong>Week 1:</strong> Order reagents from Addgene (plasmid takes 2-4 weeks to ship) and ESP32s from AliExpress (1-3 weeks shipping).<br/>
            <strong>Week 1:</strong> Order everything else from Amazon (2-day shipping).<br/>
            <strong>Week 2-3:</strong> Build hardware while waiting for plasmid. Flash firmware, test WebSocket, wire each instrument, verify in the Lab dashboard.<br/>
            <strong>Week 3-4:</strong> Plasmid arrives. Start the wizard, make your first mRNA.</p>
        </div>

        <p class="wiz-explain">For complete wiring diagrams with exact pin numbers for every single connection, see the source code files: <code>HARDWARE.md</code>, <code>DRIVERS.md</code>, and <code>SHOPPING.md</code> in the <a href="https://github.com/cruzlauroiii/rnapop.com/tree/main/src/Esp32">GitHub repository</a>.</p>
